04644nam a22006375i 9780773552708DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735527087 a10.1515/97807735527082doi  a(DE-B1597)655053  a(OCoLC)1006790590  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aND237.M665bA76 2017 7aART0160002bisacsh04a759.13223  aLI 999992rvk0(DE-625)rvk/97471:1 aEpstein, Clarence, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQuebec :bA Painting by Adam Miller /cAlexandre Turgeon, Donald Kuspit, Clarence Epstein, François-Marc Gagnon. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :bFull colour  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tNote on Adam Miller and the Painting of History -- tA History of Quebec in the Shadow of the Quiet Revolution -- tThe New Objectivism -- tInterview with Adam Miller -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe 2017 painting Quebec by Adam Miller represents over four hundred years of Quebec history. Featuring recognizable Quebec and Canadian politicians, ordinary characters, and allegorical figures, this unusual work visualizes many of the debates surrounding the 150th anniversary of Canadian Confederation as well as the 375th anniversary Montreal's founding. Bringing together a collection of commentaries on the painting and its artist, this volume contemplates the Quebec and Canadian experience and the bonds that link art and history. Included within are a reproduction of the painting, assorted detail shots, a key to the figures represented, and preparatory drawings used for the final work. Furthermore, essays by art historians François-Marc Gagnon, Donald Kuspit, and Alexandre Turgeon reflect on the painting and its style, as well as on its representation of history in relation to questions of politics, art, and collective memory. The book also contains an interview with Adam Miller conducted by Clarence Epstein, which reveals the sources of inspiration for the piece and the artist's creative process. A preface by the patron who commissioned the painting, Salvatore Guerrera, rounds out the contributions. Adam Miller is a painter known for his polished neo-classical figurative style that dramatizes historical subject matter and themes of social justice. He lives in New York.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHistory in art. 0aPaintersxHistoryx21st centuryxUnited States. 0aPolitics in art. 7aART / Individual Artists / General.2bisacsh1 aEpstein, Clarence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, François-Marc, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGagnon, François-Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuerrera, Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKuspit, Donald, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aKuspit, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTurgeon, Alexandre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773552708?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773552708423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773552708/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  